title: Import type definitions for express.static from serve-static instead
body:
of only supporting the call signature.

Express exposes serve-static as express.static: https://github.com/strongloop/express/blob/master/lib/express.js#L60
Prior to this change, the type definitions would only consist of the call signature of serve-static, but serve static also has member variables. By importing the entire type definition from serve-static and using it for express.static, both the call signature and the members can be used.

`npm test` passes both locally and on [Travis](https://travis-ci.org/rehmsen/DefinitelyTyped/builds/67404105).

This change is small, but it will remove a minor headache for me. :smiley:

The current typings use the module name "decimal", which is [a different NPM package](https://www.npmjs.com/package/decimal).

decimal.js is in the [npm package of the same name](https://www.npmjs.com/package/decimal.js). In a Node or Browserify setting, you use it with `require('decimal.js')`. Thus, I've changed the typings to use the module name 'decimal.js'.

Let me know if you have any questions.

title: React JSX support
body:
This PR refactors the React definition files in preparation for TypeScript support for JSX (https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/pull/3564)

The breakdown is now:
- `react-jsx.d.ts`: Contains most of the React definitions and the required definitions for JSX
- `react.d.ts`: The external module definition of React; defines a few things locally but mostly re-exports things from `react-jsx.d.ts` for easier maintainability
- `react-global.d.ts`: Same as `react.d.ts`, but as the global object `React`

title: Combine internal/external React .d.ts files and prepare for TS JSX
body:
This PR refactors the React definition files in preparation for TypeScript support for JSX (https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/pull/3564)

Due to limitations in TypeScript, I had to combine the .d.ts files for the internal and external module definitions for React (in the same way as e.g. jQuery's .d.ts file). This should generally be a good thing since now there's not two copies of the same code that need to be kept in sync.

body:
The main project url is accessible from :
https://github.com/devnixs/ODataAngularResources
